# Epic Completion and Drift Evaluation

## Purpose

This report certifies whether the current epic was actually completed and identifies strategic drift that occurred during implementation.

It evaluates repository reality against the projection, `.agents/epic.md`, and `.agents/milestones/*.md`.

It does not update roadmap completion context, roadmap, epic, milestone specs, or implementation.

## Authority Boundary

- The projection defines desired strategic state, constraints, and drift semantics.
- `.agents/epic.md` defines the epic’s intended capability, acceptance criteria, and success conditions.
- `.agents/milestones/*.md` define milestone-level intent, dependencies, validation strategy, and completion evidence.
- The repository is authoritative evidence of implemented reality.
- This report certifies completion and records drift.
- This report does not modify any project artifact.

## Evaluation Summary

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| Epic ID | {{epic_id_or_unknown}} |
| Epic Name | {{epic_name_or_unknown}} |
| Overall Completion Status | Fully Complete / Functionally Complete / Partially Complete / Not Complete / Inconclusive |
| Overall Drift Classification | None / Positive / Negative / Mixed / Unknown |
| Evidence Strength | Strong / Moderate / Weak / Unclear |
| Closure Recommendation | Close Epic / Close With Follow-Up / Continue Epic / Reopen Epic / Gather More Evidence |
| Primary Reason | {{one_sentence_reason}} |

## Executive Summary

Provide 2–4 short paragraphs.

Explain:

- whether the epic was completed
- what repository evidence supports or contradicts completion
- what material drift occurred
- what should happen next

Avoid implementation history.

Focus on certification and strategic implications.

